# VMware Installation Guide for Windows & macOS

## üìå Overview
VMware is a powerful virtualization platform that allows users to run multiple operating systems on a single machine. This guide provides step-by-step instructions to install VMware on Windows and macOS.

## üñ•Ô∏è Installing VMware Workstation on Windows

### ‚úÖ Prerequisites
Before proceeding with the installation, ensure your system meets the following requirements:
- **Operating System**: Windows 10 or later
- **RAM**: Minimum 4GB (8GB or more recommended)
- **Storage**: At least 20GB free disk space

### üîΩ Download VMware Workstation Player
1. Visit [TechSpot](https://www.techspot.com) and download the latest version of **VMware Workstation Player**.
2. Save the downloaded `.exe` file on your system.

### üõ†Ô∏è Install VMware Workstation Player
1. Locate the downloaded `.exe` file and double-click it to start the installation.
2. Follow the on-screen instructions:
   - Accept the **License Agreement**.
   - Choose the **Installation Path** (default recommended).
   - Select additional options like VMware Tools updates and customer experience improvement (optional).
   - Click **Install** and wait for the process to complete.
3. Once installed, click **Finish**.

### üöÄ Launch VMware Workstation Player
- Open VMware Workstation from the **Start Menu** or **Desktop Shortcut**.

## üçè Installing VMware Fusion on macOS

### ‚úÖ Prerequisites
Before installing VMware Fusion, ensure your Mac meets the following requirements:
- **Operating System**: macOS Monterey or later
- **RAM**: Minimum 4GB (8GB or more recommended)
- **Storage**: At least 20GB free disk space
- **Processor**: Intel-based Mac (VMware Fusion does not support Apple Silicon natively; use UTM instead)

### üîΩ Download VMware Fusion
1. Visit the official [VMware Fusion](https://www.vmware.com/products/fusion.html) website.
2. Download the latest version suitable for your macOS.

### üõ†Ô∏è Install VMware Fusion
1. Open the downloaded `.dmg` file.
2. Drag and drop **VMware Fusion** into the Applications folder.
3. Open VMware Fusion from **Applications**.
4. Follow the on-screen installation steps, including accepting the **License Agreement**.
5. Once installed, VMware Fusion is ready to use.

## üêß Installing Kali Linux on VMware (Windows & macOS)

### ‚úÖ System Requirements
- **RAM**: Minimum 4GB
- **Storage**: 20GB free disk space
- **Processor**: 64-bit CPU with virtualization support

### üîΩ Download Kali Linux ISO
1. Visit [Kali Linux Download](https://www.kali.org/get-kali/#kali-installer-images).
2. Download the **Kali Linux Installer ISO**.

### üîß Configure Kali Linux on VMware
1. Open VMware Workstation/Fusion and select **Create a New Virtual Machine**.
2. Upload the downloaded **Kali Linux ISO**.
3. Name the virtual machine and select **Next**.
4. Set the disk size (default recommended) and click **Next**.
5. Click **Finish** to save the configuration.

### üöÄ Install Kali Linux
1. Click **Play Virtual Machine**.
2. Select **Install**.
3. Choose **Language & Country**, then set up a **Username & Password**.
4. Follow the installation steps and wait for completion.
5. Click **Continue** to reboot into Kali Linux.

## üçè Installing Kali Linux on Apple Silicon (M1/M2) Macs using UTM

### üîΩ Download & Install UTM
1. Visit [UTM](https://mac.getutm.app/) and download the latest version.
2. Open the `.dmg` file and move UTM to the **Applications** folder.

### üîß Configure Kali Linux in UTM
1. Download the **ARM64 Kali Linux Installer** from [Kali Linux Download](https://www.kali.org/get-kali/).
2. Open **UTM** and click **Create a New Virtual Machine**.
3. Select **Virtualize** (not Emulate, as it‚Äôs much slower).
4. Choose **Linux** and upload the Kali ISO.
5. Allocate system resources (RAM, CPU, storage) based on your system capabilities.
6. Configure shared directories for easy file transfer.
7. Click **Create** and **Start** the virtual machine.

### üöÄ Install Kali Linux
1. Boot from the ISO and start installation.
2. Select **Graphical Install** or **Install** (CLI version).
3. Choose Language, Country, and set up a Username & Password.
4. Complete the installation and reboot.
5. After reboot, remove the ISO file from the virtual machine settings.

## üéØ Conclusion
By following this guide, you can successfully install and configure VMware on Windows and macOS, along with setting up Kali Linux for penetration testing and cybersecurity research. VMware provides a stable environment for running Kali Linux as a virtual machine without affecting your primary operating system.

